               <div class="col-xs-12 rmpadd" style="padding-right:0px;">
                    <p> <strong>Diego Armando Maradona</strong> (Spanish: <em>Diego Armando Maradona</em>, Spanish pronunciation: [ˈdjeɣo maɾaððona]; 30 October 1960, Lanus, Buenos Aires province, Argentina) is an Argentine footballer who played as an attacking midfielder and striker. He played for Argentinos Juniors, Boca Juniors, Barcelona, Napoli, Sevilla and Newell's Old Boys. He played 91 matches and scored 34 goals for the national team of Argentina.</p>
                    <p>World champion in 1986. Vice-world champion in 1990. Participant of four world Championships. The world champion among youth teams in 1979. The best player of the World Cup in 1986. South American Soccer Player of the Year in 1979 and 1980. Twice a member of the symbolic teams of the World Championships. Champion of Argentina in the club "Boca Juniors". Two-time champion of Italy in the club "Napoli".</p>
                    <p>The best football player of the XX century according to the voting on the official website of FIFA, where he scored 53.6 % of the votes; according to the FIFA Football Commission, Maradona is the 3rd football player in the XX century. According to the survey, the IFFIIS ranks 5th among the best football players in the world of the XX century. Ranked 2nd among the best players of the XX century by World Soccer magazine. Ranked second among the best players of the 20th century by France Football magazine. Ranked 2nd among the best players of the XX century by Guerin Sportivo. Ranked 2nd among the best players in the history of football by Placar magazine. He is the best football player in the history of the World Cups according to the newspaper The Times. It is included in the FIFA 100. The first winner of the honorary "Golden Ball". Member of the Italian Football Hall of Fame in the category "Best foreign player".</p>
                    <p>Member of the symbolic team of the best players at all FIFA World Cups. A member of the symbolic team of the best players in the history of South America. In 1999, Maradona was recognized as the best athlete of the XX century in Argentina. The author of the goal against England, called the "Goal of the Century", and recognized as the best goal in the history of the World Cups; in the same game, he scored the ball with his hand, this case is known as the "Hand of God".</p>
                    Maradona is an honorary citizen of Buenos Aires. Diego is named after the stadium of the club "Argentinos Juniors", opened on December 26, 2003 on the day of his debut in the team. In June 2005, Maradona received the Faustino Sarmiento Award from the Argentine Senate.</p>
                    <p>Maradona's sports career was cut short due to drug addiction, as a result of which he was forced to leave football for a while due to disqualification and treatment. In addition, Maradona was involved in several trials, including an arrest in April 1991 for cocaine possession and a two-year suspended sentence he received in 1999 for firing an air rifle at journalists in the summer of 1994.</p>
                    <p>After finishing his career as a player, Maradona worked as a TV commentator on the channels of Argentina and Italy. From June 2005 to August 2006, he was the vice-president of the football commission of the Boca Juniors club. He appeared in several films.</p>
                    <p>From October 2008 to July 2010, Maradona worked as the head coach of the Argentina national team, with which he reached the quarterfinals of the 2010 World Cup.
                    <p>Maradona died at the age of 60 after a heart attack that occurred on the morning of November 25, 2020. He was at his home in the San Andres district of Tigre at the time. A few days before, after Maradona underwent surgery after a brain hemorrhage.</p>
                    <p>&nbsp;</p>
                    <p><strong>Maradona's Childhood</strong></p>
                    <p>
                         <strong>
                              Early years
                         </strong>
                    </p>
                    Diego Armando Maradona was born at 5 am on Sunday, October 30, 1960 in the Evita clinic in the city of Lanus, which is located in the province of Buenos Aires. He was born in the family of Don Diego, a hereditary worker who worked at the Tritumol mill, and his wife, the housewife Dalma Salvadora Franco. Maradona was the fifth child in the family, but the first boy: before him were born four sisters-Rita, Ana, Elsa and Maria. Later, the Dalma of Salvador said: "It was easier for me than others. On Saturday, I felt fine all day, and at night I was taken to the clinic. He was born very quickly. At that moment, I only prayed for one thing: that I would be born healthy and become a good person. All this, fortunately, seems to have come true, and even I would say, with a vengeance."
                    </p>
                    <p>According to the results of the research of Narciso Binagnan, disputed, according to the author of the study, by many experts in the field of genealogy, the roots of the Maradona family came from Italy, in particular, he is a descendant of Marco Polo. Diego also has Croatian roots: Salvadora's grandmother in her maiden name was named Kariolich, and her father was a native of the island of Korcula.</p>
                    <p>At the age of 10 months, Diego learned to walk. Like most children in Argentina, Maradona started chasing the ball from an early age. What the children played was hardly football, the kids just ran around and hit the ball.</p>
                    When Maradona was 7 years old, his cousin Beto, the son of Aunt Nena, gave him the very first ball in his life. Diego was so happy with the gift that he fell asleep with it in his arms on the first night. Diego then took the ball outside to show it off in front of the court, but, deciding not to give the ball to anyone, took it home. The ball had been in Diego's room all winter, and only occasionally had he chased it around the house with his sisters. In the spring, Diego still decided to take him out into the yard: his father showed him how to hit, and his son trained for a long time against the wall, simply striking with his left foot.</p>
                    When Diego learned to hit the ball well after training, he started playing full-fledged football with the older guys. In the game, little Diego did not succeed, the older players skipped past or circled him, and the offended Maradona grabbed the ball with his hands and pressed it to himself. Gradually, Maradona got used to football and began to play like everyone else on the field. He could play for hours on a vacant lot called "Seven Glades", where yard matches were held. Diego preferred to play in the position of libero, only at a later age he switched to the attack. Gradually, Maradona became one of the most technical players in the yard, and the school teams always wanted Diego to play for them. After Maradona went to the school "Remedios de Escalada San Martin", he was almost immediately included in the football team of the Escalada, where the younger students played. In 1999, in his book, Diego wrote: "I always say that I became a professional, starting from a very young age: I played for the team that invited me first, sometimes I was not allowed to leave the house, and then I roared like crazy. Still, five minutes before our match started, Tota always gave me permission. But it took a lot more effort to convince Don Diego, my father. I understood my old man, and how could I not understand him when he was literally struggling to eat and learn? And he really wanted me to learn."</p>
                    <p>Diego's family lived in the Villa Fiorito neighborhood at the intersection of Asamor and Mario Bravo streets in a three-room house that was located on the southern outskirts of Buenos Aires and was one of the poorest in the city. Maradona's family was also in poverty, so the children, to help their parents, made clay jars for flowers, sold them at the local market and gave all the money they earned to their mother. Diego did it, too. He later said, " If my parents ask me for the moon, I will do everything I can to get it. But that would be nothing compared to what they did for me."</p>
                    <p>&nbsp;</p>
                    <p>
                         <strong> "Bulbs" </strong>
                    </p>
