                    When Maradona was 8 years old, he met Goyo Carrizo, a 10-year-old boy who played in the children's team of the club "Argentinos Juniors". Carrizo was very fond of football, and on this basis the guys became friends — the more experienced Carrizo told Maradona about the great football players of the past, in which Maradona was interested.</p>
                    < p>Carrizo, in mid-1969, introduced Maradona to Francisco Cornejo, a scout for Argentinos Juniors and coach of the under-14 team. At the first viewing of the team, Diego played so well that Cornejo did not believe in the age of Maradona, thinking that he was a dwarf. Cornejo invited Maradona to attend the training sessions of the club's adult team, where Diego, like other young players, served balls to the players. From these guys, Cornejo created the team "Los Cebolitas" ("Onions"), which was the youth team of "Argentinos Juniors". He provided them with uniforms and a field where regular training sessions were held. The team was quite strong: young players beat all the local youth teams. The leader of the "Onions" was Maradona, who had excellent technique, the ability to make the right decisions on the field and excellent physical form, thanks to which he could run both halves almost without getting tired. Another valuable quality of Diego was that after hitting his legs, he did not fall. Francisco Cornejo said: "Even then, Diego Maradona could do almost everything with the ball. He was like a wooden doll-a tumbler: no matter how much you push him, he always stays on his feet." At the same time, Diego was three years younger than the rest of the team.</p>
                    <p>With each match, the "Onions" progressed, regular victories with a double-digit score became regular. The apotheosis of their game was the match held on September 28, 1971, in which Maradona's team defeated the youth team of River Plate with a score of 7:1. In this game, Diego, who was only 10 years old at the time, scored 5 goals. At the same time, before the start of the game, he promised his injured teammate that he would score 2 goals for himself and three for him: "On the field, we were like a car. We beat everyone even with a score of 20: 0. We dreamed of playing against the famous juniors from River Plate, who were the champions of Argentina. Finally, this match took place. We won 7: 1, and I scored an amazing goal, and I scored five goals in total, as promised. You should have seen how angry the opponent was and chased me all over the field." Since that match, Maradona has been talked about as a future star of Argentine football, and the newspaper Clarín wrote an article about Diego, in which it mistakenly called him Caradona. The team played so hard that it reached a record of 136 consecutive games without defeat. Before the game with the youth team of Banfield, Diego seriously injured his hand, he had seven stitches, Cornejo did not want to let him out on the field, but Maradona persuaded the coach and was able to play in the match, where he scored 5 goals, and his club won 7:1. Along with performances in domestic competitions, the team participated in tournaments in Peru and in Uruguay. In addition to playing for the "Bulblets" Maradona played at halftime "Argentinos juniors", cutting the ball. For this skill, he was called to the television program "Sabados Circulares".</p>
                    < p>From the age of 12, Maradona played for the youth team of Argentinos Juniors. In order for Diego to play for Juniors, the head coach of the team was forced to hide the age of Diego, which was below the minimum allowed. Therefore, Maradona played for the "Red Beetles" under a false name. In 1973, the youth team of "Argentinos" won the final of the Evita Cup "River Plate" with a score of 5: 4, in this game Maradona scored a goal, beating seven people. A week after the game, William Keith, who was the president of the River Plate, offered Diego's father to buy Maradona, but he refused. The following year, the team won the championship of the ninth league of Argentina, entering the eighth league. In 1975, the club achieved a gap of 10 points from the nearest pursuer in the championship, and Diego was sent to the seventh team "Argentinos". In the seventh team, he played only two games, and he was immediately transferred to the fifth team. In the fifth team, Maradona played 4 matches and was transferred to the third team. In the third team, Diego played three games. After that, Maradona was transferred to the main squad of Argentinos Juniors.</p>
                    Despite these achievements, Maradona's family was still poor. Diego had brothers Raul and Ugo, and then a sister Claudia. The father encouraged his son's passion, taking him to the club for training every day after work, hoping that he could become a famous football player and lead the family out of poverty:</p>
                    <blockquote>
                         "My father continued to work at the mill. He always came home from work tired. He worked two shifts, morning and evening. Grain was brought almost round the clock, and fresh grinding was immediately returned to the owner. However, in the afternoon, after dinner, he would take me by the hand and take me to the club..."</p>
                    </blockquote>
