                    <p>In 1979, Maradona participated in the youth team at the South American Championship. There, the Argentines took second place, losing only to the hosts of the tournament, the national team of Uruguay. At the tournament, Diego played 5 of his team's 6 games. In the same year, as the team captain, he went to the World Youth Championship in Japan. He made his debut in the championship on August 26 in a match against Indonesia, which the Argentines won 5-0, and Diego scored two goals. At the tournament, the Argentines won all the matches, conceding only 2 goals, becoming the best team in the world, and Maradona himself, who did not play only in the 1/4 final with Algeria, was recognized as the best player of the championship and scored in each of the matches played, except for the match with Yugoslavia. In addition, in the final with the USSR national team, Maradona scored the last goal of the match, which finally "confirmed" the score in the game. According to Diego, the youth team of the 1979 model was the best team in his entire career, in which he played.</p>
                    <p>At the club level, Maradona became the top scorer of Metropolitano and Nacional, scoring 14 and 12 goals, respectively, with Argentinos Juniors. At the end of a season in which his club did not perform well, Maradona was recognized as the Best Player and best athlete of Argentina, scoring a total of 26 goals in 27 matches played. As a member of the Argentina national team in 1979, Diego scored the first goal, striking against Scotland in a friendly game on 2 June. In the same year, he, as part of the national team, went to the Copa America, where he played 2 games and scored 1 goal, hitting the gates of Bolivia. In this tournament "Albiceleste" was unsuccessful, finishing in last place in their group.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>
                    <p><strong>1980</strong></p>
                    <p>The following year, Maradona was again the top scorer of both Argentine championships with 25 and 18 goals, which allowed him to become the only player in the history of the Argentine championship, 5 times becoming the top scorer of the national championships. Diego's goals helped his club finish second in the Metropolitano. On September 14, Maradona scored his hundredth goal at the professional level, hitting the goal of San Lorenzo. However, too much media attention and Diego's constant absences from the national team had a bad effect on the attitude of the club towards Maradona. At Argentinos Juniors, half of the players did not communicate with Diego, and the club's coach demanded goals first in every match, and then in every half. In October, on the eve of the club's match with Boca Juniors, Boca goalkeeper Hugo Orlando Gatti said in an interview that Maradona is not a bad player, but the media inflate his importance too much, and also called Diego "fat". In response, Maradona in the press called Gatti envious and said that he concedes "stupid goals". Before the game, Gatti approached Diego and said that he had not said anything like that, but he did not care: Maradona, angry with the goalkeeper's words, scored 4 goals. Many people recognize that match as the best game of Diego in the "Argentinos Juniors". After the game, Maradona expected approval from the club's management, but instead of praise, he was told :" For you, this is the norm. You get paid for goals." After that, Maradona stopped going to training and began to look for a new club. The candidate to buy Maradona was River Plate, who offered Diego a salary equal to that of the team's highest-paid player, Ubaldo Fillol. But Maradona did not want to move to River: in an interview, he said that he was invited by Boca Juniors, although this was not true. After these words, Boca began negotiations on the transfer of the striker. On February 20, Maradona became a Boca Juniors player. This transition was called the "transfer of the century". Diego moved to the camp of the "Genoese" on loan with the gradual purchase of the contract of the player by the club for a total of 3 million 600 thousand dollars. This money was paid by Boca for a year and a half. Under the contract, the "Genoese" had to pay 600 thousand dollars of "lifting" to Maradona himself, but due to the team's problems with finances, the club instead of money gave Diego two apartments in the houses of businessman Tito Gurovich, in the districts of Correia y Libertador and Republica de la India.</p>
