                    <p>Just before the final tournament, Maradona said: "This championship will be mine!". The first match of the national team of Argentina was held in Mexico City. Initially, the Argentine football players rested more than they trained, they visited local museums, rode camels, gradually acclimating to the highlands. The game took place on June 2, in which Argentina easily beat South Korea with a score of 3:1. After the match, Diego accused FIFA of not taking enough care of the technical players and that the games started at 12 o'clock in the afternoon, when it was very hot. In the second game, the Argentines faced Italy, the world champion. The score was opened by the Italians, but in the 34th minute Maradona scored a return goal, which Diego himself called one of the best goals of his career; as a result, the game ended in a draw.:1. In the third game, Argentina defeated Bulgaria with a score of 2: 0 (Maradona made an assist) and advanced to the 1/8 finals. In the 1/8 final, Argentina met with Uruguay, the match was held on June 16 in the city of Puebla. In this game, Argentina won 1-0, thanks to a goal by Pedro Pasculli. This victory was the first won by Argentina over Uruguay in the final parts of the World Cups.</p>
                    <p>&nbsp;</p>
                    <p>
                         <strong>
                              Match with England
                         </strong>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                         In the 1/4 final, Argentina met with England. The game had not only a sports subtext: 4 years before the World Cup, Argentina and Great Britain fought for the Falkland Islands (Malvinas), because of which there were clashes between fans who remembered these events in the stands and outside. The match was played on June 22 at the Azteca Stadium in Mexico City. In the 51st minute, Maradona opened the scoring. Steve Hodge unsuccessfully hit the ball to his goalkeeper Peter Shilton, and Maradona, who was inferior to the goalkeeper in height of 20 cm, with his left hand, ahead of the goalkeeper, scored it into the goal. The referee of the match did not record any violations of the rules. This goal caused a fight in the stands: the British attacked the Argentines. After the game, Diego said: "I didn't touch the ball, it was the hand of God."
                    </p>
                    <p>In Italy, at the end of the match, this goal of Maradona was called "Piola's Little Hand", because of the goal scored by Silvio Piola against the British on May 13, 1939. After the goal, the English began to literally "hunt" for Maradona, especially the central defenders Terry Butcher and Terry Fenwick. A few minutes after the first goal, Diego scored a goal, beating 6 consecutive English players: Harry Stevens, Peter Reid, Steve Hodge, Terry Butcher, goalkeeper Peter Shilton and Terry Fenwick. Later, in 2002, this goal was called the best in the history of the World Championships. England manager Bobby Robson said after the game: "It was a fantastic goal." Maradona himself said: "I liked that goal. But it was just one goal. They will not win the championship...". At the end of the game, the English played one goal, and the game ended in favor of Argentina 2:1. Maradona for playing in this match was dubbed "The Michelangelo of football".</p>
                    <p>For us, for the country we represented, the game with England was the final one. We defended not just the honor of the national team, but the honor of the country. Of course, before the match, we said that football had nothing to do with the war for the Malvinas Islands, but we knew a lot of guys who died there, shot like birds. It was revenge. It's like we've recaptured a few islands. In the pre-match interviews, we all said that football and politics should not be interfered with, but this was a lie. We couldn't help but think about it. For us, winning meant more than just winning, reaching the next round and getting England out of the championship. To some extent, we blamed the English players for everything that happened, for all the suffering of the Argentine people. This feeling was stronger than us: we defended the colors of the flag, the dead guys and those who survived. I think that's why my goal meant so much. Actually, both goals. Both had their own charm.</p><div class="thumb tright" style="margin: 0.5em 0px 1.3em 1.4em; width: auto; background-color: #ffffff; clear: right; float: right; color: #222222; font-family: sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px;">
