                    <p>in the Summer of 1986 Maradona wanted to buy a new President of the club AC Milan, Silvio Berlusconi, who offered a salary twice what she paid for Napoli, as well as a luxury car, an apartment in the most prestigious area of Milan and a stake in the company Berlusconi, the "Fininvest", but Diego had refused the Rossoneri, peripodial contract with Napoli by raising wages to $ 5 million per year. Also from the president of "Napoli" he was presented with a Ferrari F40 car, at that time the only one in the world. In the same off-season, Italy midfielder Fernando De Napoli joined the Azzurri. In the first round of the 1986/1987 championship, Napoli won Brescia thanks to Maradona's only goal, but in the next round they lost to Udinese, a team that was deprived of 9 points at the start of the tournament for participating in match-fixing. Before the 7th round of the championship, Napoli was in second place in the standings and played away with Roma, the only goal in the match was scored by Maradona, who shot from 10 meters after a pass from Giordano. After this victory, and also thanks to the draw of Juventus, who shared points with Inter ,the Neapolitan club took the first place in Serie A: "This victory took off the psychological burden from us. We felt able to beat any opponent."</p>
                    On November 11, Napoli faced Juventus, the Italian champion and their main pursuer, in Turin, and won 3-1, losing during the match. After this match, the Azzurri became the leaders of the Italian championship. In the penultimate match of the first round, Napoli lost to Fiorentina 2: 3 (Maradona scored the second goal of his team) due to an error in the last minutes of goalkeeper Garella, but in the next match they beat Ascoli and became the winter champion of Serie A. In the middle of the season, the Azzurri experienced a decline that coincided with Maradona's decline in the game: the Argentine could not hit the opponents ' goal for 620 minutes (6 matches). In the 22nd round, in a match with Roma, played in a draw, Maradona suffered a minor injury, which is why he did not train for several days. In the 23rd round, the Neapolitan club lost to Inter 0: 1, and Maradona could not realize a one-on-one exit. Then there was a draw with Empoli and a defeat by Verona, in a match where Maradona, who was playing with an injury, did not score a penalty. However, after the match with Verona, Maradona said: "Right now, after this defeat, I am more confident than ever — the champion will be Napoli! Every team in the championship must have the worst match ever! We played it today. But that won't happen again. And then, we have two points left!"</p>
                    <p>However, the fans continued to express their dissatisfaction. 4 rounds before the finish, Diego reported: "I've realized lately that Naples doesn't love me anymore. Well, if the love runs out, then there will be a divorce." After that, the Neapolitan public was divided: some supported Diego, others reproached him for "childishness". On April 26, Napoli defeated AC Milan (2: 1), the decisive goal was scored by Maradona, this victory almost opened the way for the Neapolitan club to the Scudetto, won two matches later after a draw with Fiorentina. At the end of the season, Maradona extended his contract with the Azzurri for 5 years.</p>
                    <p>&nbsp;</p>
                    <p><strong>1987/1988</strong></p>
                    In the summer, Napoli played a friendly match at home with the Argentine club Rosario Central and lost 0: 1, and Maradona did not score a penalty 3 minutes before the end of the match, after which he was booed by the Neapolitan tiffosi until the final whistle. After the game, Maradona said:<br>The audience didn't understand. She does not want to show understanding and restraint. The day before yesterday I said: the team is just starting the preparatory stage and the results of the trial games do not matter much. The reaction of the audience caused me bitterness and disappointment. However, since 1989, they will not be able to boo me anymore, because as soon as my contract ends, I will leave here.</p>
                    <p>However, a few days later, the player noted that his opinion was impulsive and hasty, and in the first official game of the season, a huge banner was hung in the stands of Napoli with the inscription: "Maradona! We love you! You are forever ours!" In the same off-season, a new striker, the Brazilian Kareka, came to the club and immediately found mutual understanding on the field with Maradona, these two players, together with the Italian Giordano, formed the famous three of the "MaGiCa" attack (Maradona, Giordano and Careca).</p>
                    <p>After 12 rounds, the club scored 21 points, losing only to Pisa, but in the 13th round, the club was defeated by the main pursuer of the Neapolitans, Milan with a score of 1:4. And in the next match in the Italian Cup, he lost to Fiorentina with a score of 2:3. In the subsequent matches, the Azzurri started to win. In the first 19 rounds, Napoli scored 87 % of the points. Only in the 26th round, the club lost to Juventus, and then drew with Verona. On May 1, "Napoli" met with "Milan", which was 1 point behind the opponent and lost 2: 3, and one of the goals was scored by Maradona with a free kick. And then Diego got injured and did not play in the last matches. "Napoli" finished the championship in 2nd place. However, Diego himself was least blamed: the Argentine became the top scorer of the championship with 15 goals. Despite this, there were accusations in the press that the Neapolitan club "handed over" several games due to pressure from the structures that controlled the sweepstakes, but this was not proven.</p>
                    <p>&nbsp;</p>
                    <p><strong>1988/1989</strong></p>
                    <p>The 1988/1989 season was not very successful for Maradona — he missed several matches due to a knee injury and a back ailment. He made his first appearance in the third round, and with him in the squad, Napoli defeated Pescara with a score of 8: 2, and two of the eight goals were scored by Diego himself. However, even without him, the club, which radically changed the composition, adding players Alemao, Giuliano Giuliani and Luca Fuzi, again took 2nd place, 11 points behind the champion, Inter Milan. In the league, Maradona scored only 9 goals and scored 3 times in the UEFA Cup won by the club, more often playing along with partners than scoring on his own. In the same season, the Neapolitan club reached the final of the Italian Cup, but lost it to Sampdoria with a total score of 1: 4, and Maradona with 7 goals became the top scorer of his team in the tournament.</p>
                    <p>In the middle of the season, Diego's contract was offered to Olympique Marseille, whose president, Bernard Tapie, offered Maradona a salary twice as high as he received at Napoli and a villa with a park of 6,000 square meters. On the eve of the UEFA Cup final, the president of Napoli, Corrado Ferlaino, agreed to let Diego go to Marseille if the club wins this tournament. After winning the tournament, Ferlaino approached Maradona and said: "You're not for sale. I just wanted to motivate you."</p>
                    <p>&nbsp;</p>
                    <p><strong>1989/1990</strong></p>
                    <p>In the 1989/1990 season, Bianchi was replaced by Alberto Bigon as coach of Napoli. Maradona was unable to play at the beginning of the season due to an injury, and Gianfranco Zola took his place in the squad. Without Diego in the squad, the Neapolitan club earned only 1 point in the first three matches. However, the player later recovered from the injury and returned to the squad, which helped the club win the second Scudetto in 5 years. Maradona scored 16 goals in the tournament, becoming the third sniper after Marco van Basten and Roberto Baggio. Zola later recalled that if he had not come into contact with Maradona, he definitely would not have become such a football player later. For the young Gianfranco, Diego played the role of an older brother, from whom he learned a lot.</p>
                    <p>In the same season, the club won the Italian Super Cup, in the final of which Maradona's team beat Juventus 5-1.</p>
                    <p>&nbsp;</p>
                    <p><strong>World Cup 1990</strong></p>
                    <p>After winning the World Cup in 1986, the national team of Argentina stopped showing high results. At the 1987 Copa America, the team finished only 4th, despite the performance of Maradona, who, playing with adductor tendinitis, scored 3 of the 5 goals of the national team, including the first goal of the tournament, on June 27 in the 47th minute of the match against Peru. In the list of the best scorers of Maradona, only 1 goal was lost to the best sniper of the Cup, the Colombian Arnoldo Higuaran. In 1989, Argentina took the 3rd place, and Maradona himself, very tired (for the season he played more than 50 games) and had problems with the back of the thigh, did not score a single goal. A few months before the World Cup, Maradona even announced that he would refuse to participate in the world championship if he was not well prepared.</p>
                    <p>&nbsp;</p>
                    <p>
                         <strong>Final Tournament</strong>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                         A few days before the tournament, Maradona lost a nail on his right foot. Because of this, he could not run and train. On June 3, at the Dal Monte Institute in Rome, a protective splint made of carbon fiber was applied to Diego's nail. The very next day, Maradona held a full training session.
                    </p>
                    <p>The final tournament of the 1990 World Cup began for Argentina on June 8 with a match against Cameroon at the San Siro Stadium, and in the first game, Argentina lost 0:1. According to Maradona, the reason for the defeat was the fact that Claudio Canigia did not appear in the starting line-up of the national team, and the other forwards of the national team were "unforgettable". Another reason for the defeat, Diego called the rough game of the Cameroonians, especially Benjamin Massing, who acted personally against Maradona. The second match, against the USSR national team, was held in Naples, in the hometown of the club Diego. Argentina won 2-0, and after Oleg Kuznetsov's strike, Maradona knocked the ball off the goal line with his hand, but the referee of the match did not notice the episode. In the third game, also held in Naples, Argentina drew 1-1 with Romania (Diego provided an assist) and exited the group from third place thanks to the higher number of points scored compared to the other third-placed teams in their groups. In the game against Romania, Maradona received a painful blow to the ankle of his left foot, which is why he played in the remaining matches on painkillers.</p>
                    <p>In the 1/8 final, Argentina met with Brazil, which was played by Diego's partners in "Napoli" - Kareka and Alemao. Most of the match, the Brazilians had a huge advantage, and only due to luck and the second Argentine goalkeeper Goicoechea their gates were not touched (repeatedly after the ball strikes the Brazilians had hit the woodwork), but in the 81st minute, Maradona made his signature pass, beating several players of the Brazilian national team, being surrounded by three opponents, Diego could, falling, twisting his leg and give a very accurate pass between the legs of the opponent on Claudio Canigou, which, in turn, scored the winning goal. At the stage of the 1/4 final, Argentina defeated Yugoslavia in a penalty shootout, while Maradona did not score his penalty.</p>
                    <p>In the semifinals, the Argentines faced the hosts of the tournament, the Italians, who had previously won all the matches in the tournament. The game was played in Naples. On the eve of the match, Diego gave an interview in which he said: "I don't like how everyone now calls on Neapolitans to be Italian and support the national team. Naples has always been isolated from the rest of Italy. This city has always suffered from unfair racism." After the interview, the head of Napoli fans, Gennaro Montuori, said: "We will support Italy, while respecting and applauding Argentina." The game itself had posters with the words: "Diego in our hearts, Italy in our songs", "Maradona, Naples loves you, but Italy is our Homeland". The game ended in a 1-1 draw, and the Argentines won the penalty shootout. Maradona scored the winning penalty. After the game, at the team's home base, an unknown person tore down the flag of Argentina, which infuriated Diego.</p>
                    <p>In the final, Argentina lost to the German team with a score of 0: 1 after an undisputed penalty, scored by the Germans. In this game, Maradona was remembered for receiving the last yellow card in the tournament. The reason for the poor performance of Diego in the final was called the game of Lothar Matteus, who personally acted against Maradona. When the match ended, Maradona burst into tears on the pitch. The post-match reward ended in a scandal: Maradona refused to shake the hand of the president of FIFA, Brazilian Joao Avelange, believing that he had deliberately arranged so that the Argentines did not win. For his performance at the World Cup, Diego received the "Bronze Ball" as the third player of the World Cup.</p>
                    <p>On October 11, a few months after the end of the World Cup, Maradona announced:</p>
                    <blockquote>
                         <p>I will no longer play for the national team. I thought about this decision for a long time and made my choice. He hurts me, but I leave the post of captain in my favorite team, but I have to do it. I was lied to, I was pushed out of the team. Joao Avelange was treated like a king during his visit to Argentina, as if nothing had happened. To top it all off, Julio Grondona wrote a letter to Viola, the president of Roma, thanking us for the way he treated us, and for who knows what else. I mean, Ruggieri, Giusti brown — we're all idiots?! They didn't even notice how badly we were treated in Italy! Grondon is the vice-president of FIFA, but when we were robbed of the victory in the final, he did not lift a finger! Despite all the pain of this decision, despite the fact that I really like being the captain of the national team, I'm leaving.</p>
                    </blockquote>
                    <p>&nbsp;</p>
                    <p><strong>1990/1991</strong></p>
                    <p>After the 1990 World Cup, Maradona fired his agent Guillermo Coppola and appointed a new one, Marcos Franchi. The football season started positively — "Napoli" won the Italian Super Cup. After that, Maradona played another 24 games, in which he scored 10 goals. In the Champions League, the Neapolitan team played poorly, losing to Spartak Moscow; at the same time, Diego did not arrive with the team for the decisive return game, but a day later on a private plane. On March 17, 1991, after the match of the 25th round of the Italian championship with Bari, won 1-0, the player was selected among the players who must pass a doping test. The test revealed the presence of cocaine in Diego's system. The Italian Football Federation has decided to disqualify Maradona for a period of 15 months. The lawyers tried to challenge the disqualification, but the appeals committee upheld the decision. On March 24, a few days before his suspension, Maradona played his last game for Napoli: his club lost 1-4 to Sampdoria»; the only goal of the Neapolitans was scored by Diego from the penalty spot.</p>
                    <p>According to Maradona, the tests were tampered with thanks to the intervention of the president of the Italian Football Federation, Antonio Mattarrese, who avenged Diego for the defeat of the Italian national team against Argentina at the 1990 World Cup. Maradona himself claimed that although he took drugs, he always conducted doping tests on his own, so that on the eve of the games there was no trace of the drugs taken in his body.</p>
                    On April 1, Maradona decided to return to Argentina, saying that he wanted to devote all his time to his family, and that he was tired of football. On April 26, at Diego's house on Franklin Street in the Caballito district, Maradona and two of his friends were arrested for drug possession: 36 grams of cocaine were found in his possession. The next day, after paying a bail of 20,000 pesos, Maradona was released from custody. Prior to the trial, Judge Amelia Berras de Vidal ordered Diego to undergo rehabilitation. According to Diego, the entire detention procedure was staged by the Argentine authorities. In September 1991, Maradona was sentenced in absentia in Italy to 14 months of probation for cocaine found in the basement of his home.</p>
                    <p>During the rehabilitation process, which was supposed to help Diego get rid of a long-term addiction (he first tried drugs while playing for Barcelona), Maradona decided to participate in various charity matches. On August 3, 1991, Diego played a match in favor of the Fernandez Hospital. He was supposed to play in a match dedicated to the memory of Juan Hilberto Funes, a football player who died on January 11; at the moment of death, Maradona was with him. However, on April 15, FIFA sent a fax to AFA President Julio Grondone, in which it did not approve of the possibility of Maradona playing in the match and indicated that for his participation, other players may be subject to some sanctions, according to the current rules. However, the players who took part in this game made a unanimous decision on the presence of Diego on the field, for which the referees who are not members of the AFA were invited to serve the match, and the organization itself, thus, withdrew from the organization of the match. On FIFA's conduct, Maradona said: "No one in Argentina will cry for Blatter, Avelange and other officials after their deaths." On February 27, 1992, Maradona played a match, all the fees from which went to disabled children. In the city of Posadas, Diego played a game, the fees from which went to the local hospital. Maradona also played mini-football in the TV program "Rhythms of the Night".</p>
                    <p>&nbsp;</p>
                    <p>
                         <strong>Sevilla</strong>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                         On July 1, 1992, Maradona's 15-month suspension ended. "Napoli" wanted to see the player again in their squad, but Diego wanted to leave Italy and play in a club that would not set itself big tasks in tournaments. He said :" My time at Napoli is definitely over and the Neapolitans are not likely to be so happy about my return." And after the arrival of the head coach of the team, Claudio Ranieri, who said that while he was coaching Napoli, Maradona would not come to Naples even as a tourist, Diego was determined to leave the team. There were talks about Maradona's transfer to Sevilla or Olympique Marseille. As a result, the case was decided in favor of the Spanish club, which was the first to offer $ 7.5 million for the transfer of the forward. On 22 September, Maradona became a Sevilla player. Maradona moved to Sevilla, largely thanks to the club's head coach, Carlos Bilardo, who was very eager to see Diego in his team. The president of Sevilla said: "I understood that Maradona is not the same and is not in the best shape, but I invited him for the sake of the fans. And even though it cost a lot of money, I considered myself the happiest of people. A dream came true — Maradona played in my team."
                    </p><p>&nbsp;</p>

                    <p><strong style="font-size: 16px;">Last years of the career</strong></p>
                    <p><strong>«Newells Old Boys»</strong></p>
                    In 1993, Maradona returned to Argentine football, signing a contract with Newell's Old Boys on September 9. Initially, he wanted to return to Argentinos Juniors, but after threats from the club's fans demanding to pay 50 thousand dollars, Diego chose to move to a more relaxed Rosario. On September 13, 1993, Maradona's first training session as a member of the Red and Black team was held; more than 40 thousand people gathered there. On 10 October, he made his debut for the club in a match against Independiente, in which his club lost 1-3; Diego scored the only goal of his team, hitting the goal with a heel kick. On December 2, 1993, in a match against Uracan, Maradona suffered a small muscle tear in his left leg, which was why he was released from training for 2 weeks. During Diego's absence, Newells coach Jorge Raul Solari, who had invited Maradona, was fired. His place was taken by Jorge Castelli, whose relationship with Diego did not work out. The reason for this was the agreement of the football player with Solari, to which Castelli did not agree. Maradona's last match for the club was against Vasco da Gama on 26 January 1994. On February 1, the player's contract with the club was terminated. In total, Diego played 5 official matches for the "Lepers".</p>
                    On February 2, 1994, Maradona attacked journalists and photojournalists who were reporting outside his home in Moreno with an air rifle. For this, he was sentenced to 2 years of probation, and was forced to compensate the moral and physical damage to the injured journalists.</p>
                    <p>&nbsp;</p>
                    <p><strong style=" font-size: 16px;">World Cup 1994</strong></p>
                    <p><strong>Qualifying Matches</strong></p>
                    <p>After his return to football, Maradona played only 2 matches for the national team of Argentina. Head coach Alfio Basile did not trust Diego, who did not play a single match in the qualifying tournament for the 1994 World Cup, playing only in friendly matches. Without him, the Argentine team performed poorly. After a 0-5 loss to Colombia, Basile, on 23 September 1993, officially asked Maradona to return to the national team, which was preparing for the decisive matches of the qualifying stage with Australia. With the help of Maradona, who made an assist in the first game, Argentina won with a total score of 2: 1 and qualified for the final tournament. 18 years after these two meetings, Diego said that at the behest of the President of the football Association of Argentina Julio Grondona, on the eve of the second game the players were given a special coffee containing doping, after which they "ran a lot more"; moreover, Grondona was able to do so after the meeting was not held a doping test.</p>
                    <p>At the preparatory matches, Maradona again got into trouble: Japan, where the national team flew to a friendly game, refused Diego a visa because of his drug problems. On 20 April, in a friendly match against Morocco, Maradona scored a goal for the national team, for the first time since 21 May 1990.</p>
                    <p>&nbsp;</p>
                    <p> <strong>Final Tournament</strong></p>
                    <p>The first game of the national team of Argentina in the final tournament of the World Championship was held on June 21 with Greece. In it, the Argentines won with a score of 4: 0, and Maradona, playing "in the wall" with Fernando Redondo, scored in this game his last goal at the World Championships. After the game he said: "I dedicate this match to the skeptics who claimed that I am no longer capable of anything. I'd like to hear what they're saying today." The second game Argentina won again, winning Nigeria with a score of 2:1, with the decisive goal was scored from a pass from Maradona. After the game, Diego passed a doping test. Before the last group game against Bulgaria, Maradona was informed that he had tested positive for 5 substances: ephedrine, norephedrine, pseudoephedrine, norpsevdoephedrine and methylephedrine. Maradona's suspension was 15 months.</p>
                    Without Diego, Argentina lost their two remaining matches. After the Bulgaria game, Redondo told Maradona: "I was looking for you, I was looking for you on the pitch and I couldn't find you… I've been looking for you all match." Regarding doping, Diego said that these substances were in his flu medicine and nasal drops, which his personal doctor, Daniel Serrini, bought for him in the United States, and that he did not take the banned drugs himself. After the disqualification, Diego uttered his famous phrase: "My legs were cut off." The match against Nigeria in Boston was Maradona's last match in the national team of Argentina. In total, he played 91 matches and scored 34 goals in the national team shirt.</p>
                    <p>&nbsp;</p>
                    <p><strong style="font-size: 16px;">Performances (1994-1997)</strong></p>
                    <p>
                         <strong>
                              Coaching career
                         </strong>
                    </p>
                    Maradona was disqualified for 15 months, until September 15, 1995. The suspension only applied to Diego's football performances, so he began looking for a club where he could show his administrative skills. On 3 October 1994, Maradona was appointed, along with Carlos Fresn, head coach of the club "Mandiu". In his debut match under the leadership of Diego, "Mandiu" lost to the club "Rosario Central" with a score of 1: 2; while Diego himself managed the club from the box of honor due to the fact that at that time he did not have a coaching license. Two months into the job, Osvaldo Cruz, one of the club's owners, came into the locker room and insulted the players. Maradona dismissed him, saying that only the coaches could be in the locker room. Cruz asked him: "Who are you?" After that, Diego beat Cruz and submitted his resignation on December 6. During Maradona's tenure, the club held 12 meetings, of which it won one, drew 6 and lost 5. The best result of the club in that period was a draw with River Plate. Immediately after his dismissal from the "Mandiu", Maradona replaced his representative Marcos Franchi with Guillermo Coppola, with whom he had already worked for several years before. On January 6, 1995, Maradona and Fren were hired by Racing from Avellaneda. In this club, Diego worked for 4 months, with him "Racing" played 11 matches, of which he won two, drew 6 and lost 3.
                    </p>
                    <p>&nbsp;</p>
                    <p><strong>Boca Juniors</strong></p>
                    <p>After an unsuccessful coaching debut, Maradona expressed a desire to start working as a playing coach of the club "Boca Juniors". But against this there were two circumstances: the first — the head coach of the club was Silvio Marsolini, whom the club's management did not want to dismiss, the second — the "Genoese" could not give Maradona the salary to which he was accustomed during his performances. Both of these circumstances were resolved by Diego himself: he refused to try to move to the position of coach of the team, and also agreed that his salary would be paid by several businessmen-fans of Boca, led by Eduardo Eurnekian. Maradona preferred the contract with Boca to the contract with the Brazilian "Santos", where he was invited by Pele, who offered Diego the position of playing coach. Also, the management of the club went to meet Diego and, at his request, bought Claudio Canigia. After signing the contract, Maradona started working hard to get in shape. At the same time, he starred in a small role in the film "El día que Maradona conoció a Gardel". Also on September 18, 1995, Maradona organized the "International Association of Professional Footballers" in Paris, which included Eric Cantona, George Weah, Gianluca Vialli, Gianfranco Zola, Laurent Blanc, Thomas Brolin, Rai, Ciro Ferrara and Michel Prudhomme.</p>
                    <p>
                         Maradona's official return to football took place on September 30 in Seoul, where Boca Juniors faced South Korea and won 2-1. The same week, Maradona held a conference at Oxford University, telling students about his life and the newly formed association of professional football players. On 15 October 1995, Maradona scored his first goal after being disqualified, bringing the Genoese a 1-0 win over his former team, Argentinos Juniors. Boca had a poor first Opening after Maradona's return: the club finished only 4th, and Diego scored only 3 goals in 11 games. At the same time, he missed some of the matches due to injury, and in the absence of Diego, the club scored only 1 point out of 12 possible. It wasn't until Maradona returned to action that Boquita started to win. As a result of an unsuccessful performance in the club, both the president and the coach were replaced. Despite this, Maradona expressed a desire to return to the national team of Argentina, for which he had previously refused to play, because " the people are asking for it." He was also supported by the President of Argentina, Carlos Menem. In 1996, the team's management decided to appoint Carlos Bilardo, Maradona's former coach in the national team, as head coach. Initially, Maradona threatened to leave the club if it was headed by Bilardo, but then supported the mentor. In the same season, a new president, Mauricio Macri, came to the club, with whom Diego had several run-ins, including a public altercation on the radio. In the Apertura, Boca Juniors took the 5th place, and in the overall table — the 4th position. Maradona himself did not demonstrate a high level of play this season: he played 13 matches and scored 2 goals, and in the game with Racing he did not score a penalty, which became the 5th consecutive unrealized 11-meter shot. He said: "I am destroyed... I want to die." After that, Diego played another match, on August 11 with Estudiantes ,and then he refused to play for the club. He hasn't been on the field for 11 months. In August, having already completed his performances, Maradona was acquitted by a court after accusations that he had switched his jar of urine with a jar of Alberto Vargas, who was found to have doped.
                         In the summer of 1996, Guillermo Coppola reported that the player had signed a contract worth $ 20 million with a Japanese club, but the deal did not take place due to the country's legislation prohibiting entry to any person convicted of possession, use or transportation of narcotic drugs.
                    </p>
                    <p>In the same year, Maradona was an active participant in the "Sunshine without Drugs" campaign organized by the Government of Argentina: "I did it for the kids. Drugs are everywhere, and I don't want them to take over children." In August 1996, Maradona went to Switzerland, to the Bellele clinic, where he wanted to undergo treatment for cocaine addiction: "I want to be completely cleansed of this evil. I have to do this for my daughters. The hospital in Switzerland was recommended to me by a friend of mine. It is more expensive to be treated in Argentina: doctors only demand money and do not bring any benefit." Diego spent 10 days there. After that, Maradona returned to his homeland, on the way where he participated in an exhibition game in Canada.</p>
                    <p>In the fall of 1996, Maradona created a foundation to financially support Boca Juniors. In October, 500 grams of cocaine were found in Maradona's home. In December, Maradona expressed his desire to replace Carlos Bilardo as coach of the "Genoese". Also on December 29, he took part in a charity game, all funds from which went to the paralyzed player Pablo Forlan. In January 1997, Diego held talks with the club "Barcelona" (Guayaquil), where he was going to perform the role of playing coach. In the same month, he said that he would probably play for the Uruguayan "Peñarol". However, the club from Montevideo rejected the idea of inviting the Argentine.</p>
                    <p>
                         In February 1997, Diego opened a chain of restaurants catering chain "Maradona Sports Cafes". On April 7, 1997, Diego was admitted to the hospital due to very high blood pressure, which rose during his participation in the Chilean television program "Viva el Lunes" (Live on Monday) on Canal 13.
                         On April 22, 1997, Maradona signed a new contract with Boca Juniors, despite having refused to renew it a few months earlier. In order to get in shape, Diego hired the famous track and field athlete Ben Johnson as a coach, who was paid $ 1,000 a day. On 9 July, Maradona took the field for the first time after a long break in a friendly match against Newells Old Boys and scored a goal with a free kick. On July 13, Diego appeared in an official game for the first time after a long break, in which Boca defeated Racing 3-2, and Diego participated in all three of his team's goals. This match started with a 20-minute delay due to press photographers who did not want to leave the field to take pictures of Diego. In July, a strike of professional football players in Argentina began, which Diego not only did not support, but also called "idiotic", apologizing on behalf of all the players of the national championship. In the same season, Maradona insisted on buying Boka Martin Palermo, who later became the top scorer in the team's history.
                    </p>
                    <p>On August 24, he played in the match in which Boquita defeated Argentinos Juniors 4:2, and Diego himself, having converted a penalty, scored the 150th goal in the Argentine championship. After that game, Maradona passed a doping test that tested positive for methylecgonine and benzoylecgonine, the metabolites of cocaine. He was disqualified until re-analysis, which, later, also gave a positive result. In June, Diego went to the police, claiming that he himself did not take anything and was deliberately poisoned. Moreover, a month before the match, in which doping was discovered, Maradona began to receive calls threatening to" plant " drugs on him. Later, Diego swore to his daughters that he did not take doping. Judge Claudio Bonadio confirmed that such threats against Maradona had taken place, and decided not to impose sanctions against Diego, up to the DNA test that gave a positive result of tests. He also ordered Maradona to be tested for doping after each match.
                    <p>Despite the fact that Maradona was given permission to perform, he was unable to perform for a month due to an injury sustained in the Super Cup Libertadores game with Colo-Colo. Diego returned to the field on October 25, 1997, in a game in which Boca defeated its principal rival, River Plate, with a score of 2:1. In this game, Maradona was replaced after the break by Juan Riquelme, having suffered a recurrence of the injury. This match was the last for Maradona, held at the professional level. On October 30, his 37th birthday, Maradona announced his retirement.</p>
                    <p>&nbsp;</p>
                    <p>
                         <strong style="font-size: 16px;">Game style</strong>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                         Maradona had excellent technique, used various non-football techniques: throwing, throwing, rolling the ball, which he did at a very high speed, thanks to which he circled many opponents. Also, Diego had a very accurate pass and a great left-foot shot from the game and from the penalty area, which he trained since childhood. At the same time, Diego could shoot from any position and score goals for every taste.
                    </p>
                    <p>Maradona had a very good vision of the field, thanks to which he could make assists for strikers in the club and the national team. He stood out for his focus on the fight: even if he lost the ball, he "took care" of the opponent until the ball returned to his team.</p>
                    <p>Also, Diego was extremely stable on the field and well-developed leg muscles, which allowed him to stay in a standing position after hitting his legs. It was also distinguished by the coordination of the body.</p>
                    <p>Maradona's technique was the prototype for the dribbling of Ronaldinho, who was "crazy about everything he did".</p>
                    <p>According to Arrigo Sacchi, thanks to Diego, all the teams in which he played, began to play football at a much higher level.</p>
