                    <p>In January 2000, Maradona was placed in the Cantegril sanatorium while in the Uruguayan city of Punta del Este, where he was having a party in the company of a drug dealer. He was admitted to the hospital with a hypertensive crisis and cardiac arrhythmia. His representative, Guillermo Coppola, said that it was not due to drugs, but because of nervous overexertion. However, traces of cocaine were found in his blood and urine, for which Diego was brought before the Uruguayan justice. Since no drugs were found in his possession, no charges were filed. After leaving the clinic on January 18, Diego left for Cuba, settling in a closed clinic in El Kinke, 700 km from Havana, where he spent a course of treatment and rehabilitation.</p>
                    <p>On November 10, 2001, Maradona, for the first time after a long break, appeared on the field participating in the match of the national team of Argentina and the world team, which included Enzo Francescoli, Eric Cantona, Davor Shuker, Juan Roman Riquelme, Carlos Valderrama, Rene Igita and other players. This match was a farewell for Diego, who played 1 half for the national team, and the second for the world team. The game ended in favor of Argentina 6: 3, and Maradona scored 2 goals. After the game, he uttered one of his most famous phrases: "I made a mistake and paid for the mistake. But you can't get the ball dirty!" In honor of Diego, the number 10 was permanently removed from the national team's number rotation. FIFA later changed this decision. In the same year, he signed a contract to participate in the exhibition game of veterans and artists in Moscow, but violated the terms of the contract and did not come to the game.</p>
                    <p>In 2002, Diego again commented on the World Cup matches for the Mexican channel Televisia and the multinational Direct TV. The Japanese leadership even lifted the ban on the entry of Diego. In the summer of 2002, Diego released a CD, the main hit on which was called "The Hand of God", all proceeds from which went to the hospital for destitute children of Pedro Elisalde.</p>
                    <p>In April 2004, Maradona was again admitted to the hospital with a diagnosis of a heart attack. His heart problems were aggravated by his increased weight and drug addiction, which is why, after being discharged from the hospital, he was placed in a clinic on May 9, where he underwent a course of detoxification. When Diego was cured he said: "I remember in one movie — "Heaven can wait" - a man dies, finds himself in a tunnel, but there begins to protest, believing that his death hour has not yet come. That's the tunnel I've been in. And I saw in it the fans of "River Plate", "San Lorenzo", "Racing", "Uracan", "Independiente"...". After 3 months, Maradona asked the court to give him the opportunity to move to Cuba. This was due to the fact that Diego could not leave the hospital without the consent of the family exercising custody of him, according to the court decision. In addition, Elena Bortiri, the lawyer of the Maradona family, used article 152 of the Argentine Civil Code, and partially deprived Diego of legal capacity because of his drug addiction; according to this article, the family had to become the guardian of the drug addict and take care of the person. Diego was forced to turn to the country's president, Nestor Kirchner, to help him fly to Cuba. Due to the fact that his request was not fulfilled, Maradona continued the course of treatment at home. In December 2004, Maradona, who was late for a plane, organized a pogrom with friends in the VIP lounge of the Rio de Janeiro airport.</p><div class="thumb tright" style="margin: 0.5em 0px 1.3em 1.4em; width: auto; background-color: #ffffff; clear: right; float: right; color: #222222; font-family: sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px;">
